   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d510e3d5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# HR Data Quality Analyser\n",
    "\n",
    "When I worked as an Oracle Fusion HCM consultant, one of the most frustrating parts of every migration project was the source data. Clients would hand over employee records exported from their legacy systems — and almost every time, there were problems. Duplicate person numbers, hire dates that came after termination dates, employees assigned to department codes that didn't exist in the new system.\n",
    "\n",
    "We caught most of these during SIT/UAT, but it was always manual — open the HDL file, scan through rows, flag issues in a spreadsheet, send back to the client. There was no quick way to get a summary.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook is my attempt to automate that. It takes an employee dataset (simulated here to reflect the IT/tech consulting firms I worked with), checks for the most common issues I actually encountered, and visualises the results.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Checks covered:**\n",
    "- Duplicate person numbers\n",
    "- Missing required fields\n",
    "- Date logic errors (hire date after termination date, future hire dates)\n",
    "- Invalid department codes\n",
    "- Salary outliers by grade\n",
    "- Headcount by department\n",
    "- Hire vs exit trend over time\n",
    "- Employees still in probation period\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "ab13f858",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from datetime import date\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.set_theme(style=\"darkgrid\", palette=\"muted\")\n",
    "pd.set_option(\"display.max_columns\", 20)\n",
    "pd.set_option(\"display.width\", 120)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3eff0b81",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Load the dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset simulates 300 employee records from an IT/tech consulting firm mid-migration. I've deliberately seeded it with the kinds of issues I used to find: duplicate person numbers, a few records with missing names, some bad hire/termination dates, and a handful of employees mapped to department codes that weren't in the approved list.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cce4bbfd",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "np.random.seed(7)\n",
    "n = 300\n",
    "\n",
    "departments_valid = [\"ENG\", \"HR\", \"FIN\", \"OPS\", \"SALES\", \"LEGAL\", \"IT\"]\n",
    "departments_dirty = departments_valid + [\"MKTG_OLD\", \"ADMIN2\", \"UNKNOWN\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "grades = [\"G1\", \"G2\", \"G3\", \"G4\", \"G5\"]\n",
    "salary_by_grade = {\"G1\": (30000, 40000), \"G2\": (40000, 55000),\n",
    "                   \"G3\": (55000, 75000), \"G4\": (75000, 100000), \"G5\": (100000, 150000)}\n",
    "\n",
    "grade_col = np.random.choice(grades, n, p=[0.25, 0.30, 0.25, 0.12, 0.08])\n",
    "salary_col = [\n",
    "    int(np.random.uniform(*salary_by_grade[g])) for g in grade_col\n",
    "]\n",
  
    "for i in [12, 45, 78, 130, 200]:\n",
    "    salary_col[i] = salary_col[i] * 3\n",
    "\n",
    "hire_years = np.random.randint(2018, 2024, n)\n",
    "hire_months = np.random.randint(1, 13, n)\n",
    "hire_days = np.random.randint(1, 28, n)\n",
    "hire_dates = [date(y, m, d) for y, m, d in zip(hire_years, hire_months, hire_days)]\n",
    "\n",
  
    "is_active = np.random.choice([True, False], n, p=[0.72, 0.28])\n",
    "exit_dates = []\n",
    "for i, active in enumerate(is_active):\n",
    "    if not active:\n",
    "        exit_year = hire_years[i] + np.random.randint(1, 4)\n",
    "        exit_month = np.random.randint(1, 13)\n",
    "        exit_dates.append(date(min(exit_year, 2024), exit_month, 15))\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        exit_dates.append(None)\n",
    "\n",
 
    "for i in [5, 19, 67, 88, 145]:\n",
    "    if exit_dates[i] is not None:\n",
    "        hire_dates[i] = date(2025, 6, 1)  

    "for i in [210, 255]:\n",
    "    hire_dates[i] = date(2026, 9, 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "person_numbers = [f\"EMP{str(i).zfill(5)}\" for i in range(1001, 1001 + n)]\n",
   
    "for i in [30, 30, 75, 75, 110]:\n",
    "    person_numbers[i] = person_numbers[i - 1]\n",
    "\n",
    "first_names = ([\"Arun\", \"Priya\", \"Raj\", \"Divya\", \"Karthik\", \"Meena\",\n",
    "                \"Suresh\", \"Kavya\", \"Vikram\", \"Anitha\"] * 30)[:n]\n",
    "last_names  = ([\"Kumar\", \"Sharma\", \"Patel\", \"Reddy\", \"Nair\", \"Iyer\",\n",
    "                \"Singh\", \"Pillai\", \"Rao\", \"Menon\"] * 30)[:n]\n",
    "\n",

    "for i in [14, 55, 99, 188]:\n",
    "    first_names[i] = None\n",
    "\n",
    "dept_col = np.random.choice(departments_dirty, n,\n",
    "    p=[0.20, 0.15, 0.15, 0.15, 0.15, 0.05, 0.05, 0.03, 0.03, 0.04])\n",
    "\n",
    "probation_months = 6\n",
    "probation_cutoff = date(2024, 1, 1)\n",
    "in_probation = [\n",
    "    is_active[i] and hire_dates[i] >= probation_cutoff\n",
    "    for i in range(n)\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "df = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    \"person_number\":    person_numbers,\n",
    "    \"first_name\":       first_names,\n",
    "    \"last_name\":        last_names,\n",
    "    \"department_code\":  dept_col,\n",
    "    \"grade\":            grade_col,\n",
    "    \"annual_salary\":    salary_col,\n",
    "    \"hire_date\":        hire_dates,\n",
    "    \"termination_date\": exit_dates,\n",
    "    \"is_active\":        is_active,\n",
    "    \"in_probation\":     in_probation,\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "df[\"hire_date\"] = pd.to_datetime(df[\"hire_date\"])\n",
    "df[\"termination_date\"] = pd.to_datetime(df[\"termination_date\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "df.to_csv(\"employee_data.csv\", index=False)\n",
    "print(f\"Records loaded: {len(df)}\")\n",
    "df.head(10)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "be391e9f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "First thing I always do — check shape, dtypes, and how many nulls exist before running any checks.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "43082600",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Shape:\", df.shape)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(df.dtypes)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(\"Null counts:\")\n",
    "print(df.isnull().sum())\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4e2f0561",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
  
    "\n",
    "Person number is the unique identifier in Oracle HCM (equivalent to `PersonNumber` in the Worker HDL file). Duplicates here mean two records will try to create or update the same person — one will fail, and you won't always know which one until you check the error log.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "8c7beaca",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dupes = df[df.duplicated(subset=\"person_number\", keep=False)]\n",
    "print(f\"Duplicate person numbers found: {dupes['person_number'].nunique()} person numbers, {len(dupes)} rows\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(dupes[[\"person_number\", \"first_name\", \"last_name\", \"department_code\", \"hire_date\"]].sort_values(\"person_number\"))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "01e6daf1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "In HDL, `first_name` is a required field on the Name record. If it's blank, the load either fails or creates a record with no name — which then causes issues downstream in payroll and self-service.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "2a168463",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "missing_name = df[df[\"first_name\"].isnull()]\n",
    "print(f\"Records with missing first_name: {len(missing_name)}\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(missing_name[[\"person_number\", \"last_name\", \"department_code\", \"hire_date\"]])\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1078fc26",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "Two types of date problems I ran into regularly:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Hire date after termination date** — impossible, but it happens when the source data has been manually edited\n",
    "2. **Future hire dates on active employees** — sometimes a placeholder date gets left in for employees not yet onboarded, then accidentally included in the migration batch\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "45bb9828",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "today = pd.Timestamp(date.today())\n",
    "\n",

    "bad_dates = df[\n",
    "    df[\"termination_date\"].notna() &\n",
    "    (df[\"hire_date\"] > df[\"termination_date\"])\n",
    "]\n",
    "print(f\"Hire date after termination date: {len(bad_dates)} records\")\n",
    "print(bad_dates[[\"person_number\", \"hire_date\", \"termination_date\"]])\n",
    "print()\n",
    "\n",
\
    "future_hire = df[\n",
    "    df[\"is_active\"] &\n",
    "    (df[\"hire_date\"] > today)\n",
    "]\n",
    "print(f\"Active employees with future hire dates: {len(future_hire)} records\")\n",
    "print(future_hire[[\"person_number\", \"first_name\", \"hire_date\"]])\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b9271d77",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "Every client has a reference list of approved department codes that exist in the new Oracle HCM setup. Employees mapped to codes outside that list will fail assignment creation — they load as a person but have no job assignment, which breaks everything downstream.\n",
    "\n",
    "Below I check how many employees are mapped to codes not in the approved list.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c1e2497f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "valid_dept_codes = [\"ENG\", \"HR\", \"FIN\", \"OPS\", \"SALES\", \"LEGAL\", \"IT\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "invalid_dept = df[~df[\"department_code\"].isin(valid_dept_codes)]\n",
    "print(f\"Records with invalid department codes: {len(invalid_dept)}\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(invalid_dept[\"department_code\"].value_counts())\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(invalid_dept[[\"person_number\", \"first_name\", \"department_code\"]].head(10))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f4c06c65",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "Salary data from legacy systems often has errors — a manually entered value that didn't go through approval, or a copy-paste mistake. I flag anyone whose salary is more than 2 standard deviations from the mean for their grade.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "80790ce5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "grade_stats = df.groupby(\"grade\")[\"annual_salary\"].agg([\"mean\", \"std\"]).reset_index()\n",
    "grade_stats.columns = [\"grade\", \"mean_salary\", \"std_salary\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "df2 = df.merge(grade_stats, on=\"grade\")\n",
    "df2[\"z_score\"] = (df2[\"annual_salary\"] - df2[\"mean_salary\"]) / df2[\"std_salary\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "outliers = df2[df2[\"z_score\"].abs() > 2]\n",
    "print(f\"Salary outliers (|z| > 2): {len(outliers)} records\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(outliers[[\"person_number\", \"first_name\", \"grade\", \"annual_salary\", \"mean_salary\", \"z_score\"]].round(1))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "278508ee",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "All checks in one place — the kind of summary I would have emailed to the client before go-live.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "061cdb04",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "summary = pd.DataFrame([\n",
    "    {\"Check\": \"Duplicate person numbers\",        \"Issues found\": dupes[\"person_number\"].nunique()},\n",
    "    {\"Check\": \"Missing first name\",              \"Issues found\": len(missing_name)},\n",
    "    {\"Check\": \"Hire date after termination\",     \"Issues found\": len(bad_dates)},\n",
    "    {\"Check\": \"Future hire date (active emp.)\",  \"Issues found\": len(future_hire)},\n",
    "    {\"Check\": \"Invalid department code\",         \"Issues found\": len(invalid_dept)},\n",
    "    {\"Check\": \"Salary outliers by grade\",        \"Issues found\": len(outliers)},\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "summary[\"% of total records\"] = (summary[\"Issues found\"] / len(df) * 100).round(1)\n",
    "print(summary.to_string(index=False))\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(\"Total records checked:\", len(df))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6e6cd985",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "Four charts — the same things I would check when reviewing a headcount report in OTBI.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "0b6cf510",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))\n",
    "fig.suptitle(\"HR Data Quality — Employee Overview\", fontsize=14, y=1.01)\n",
    "\n",

    "dept_counts = df[df[\"is_active\"]][\"department_code\"].value_counts()\n",
    "sns.barplot(x=dept_counts.index, y=dept_counts.values, ax=axes[0, 0])\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_title(\"Active Headcount by Department\")\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_xlabel(\"Department Code\")\n",
    "axes[0, 0].set_ylabel(\"Headcount\")\n",
    "for i, v in enumerate(dept_counts.values):\n",
    "    axes[0, 0].text(i, v + 0.5, str(v), ha=\"center\", fontsize=9)\n",
    "\n",
   
    "df[\"hire_year\"] = df[\"hire_date\"].dt.year\n",
    "hires_by_year = df.groupby(\"hire_year\").size().reset_index(name=\"hires\")\n",
    "exits_df = df[df[\"termination_date\"].notna()].copy()\n",
    "exits_df[\"exit_year\"] = exits_df[\"termination_date\"].dt.year\n",
    "exits_by_year = exits_df.groupby(\"exit_year\").size().reset_index(name=\"exits\")\n",
    "trend = hires_by_year.merge(exits_by_year, left_on=\"hire_year\", right_on=\"exit_year\", how=\"outer\")\n",
    "trend = trend[trend[\"hire_year\"].between(2018, 2024)]\n",
    "axes[0, 1].plot(trend[\"hire_year\"], trend[\"hires\"], marker=\"o\", label=\"Hires\")\n",
    "axes[0, 1].plot(trend[\"hire_year\"], trend[\"exits\"], marker=\"o\", label=\"Exits\", linestyle=\"--\")\n",
    "axes[0, 1].set_title(\"Hire vs Exit Trend (by Year)\")\n",
    "axes[0, 1].set_xlabel(\"Year\")\n",
    "axes[0, 1].set_ylabel(\"Count\")\n",
    "axes[0, 1].legend()\n",
    "\n",

    "sns.boxplot(data=df, x=\"grade\", y=\"annual_salary\", order=grades, ax=axes[1, 0])\n",
    "axes[1, 0].set_title(\"Salary Distribution by Grade\")\n",
    "axes[1, 0].set_xlabel(\"Grade\")\n",
    "axes[1, 0].set_ylabel(\"Annual Salary (£)\")\n",
    "axes[1, 0].yaxis.set_major_formatter(plt.FuncFormatter(lambda x, _: f\"£{x:,.0f}\"))\n",
    "\n",
  
    "sns.barplot(data=summary, x=\"Issues found\", y=\"Check\", ax=axes[1, 1], palette=\"Reds_r\")\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_title(\"Data Quality Issues by Check\")\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_xlabel(\"Records flagged\")\n",
    "axes[1, 1].set_ylabel(\"\")\n",
    "for i, v in enumerate(summary[\"Issues found\"]):\n",
    "    axes[1, 1].text(v + 0.1, i, str(v), va=\"center\", fontsize=9)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.savefig(\"hr_data_quality_overview.png\", dpi=150, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2cade7db",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 10. Probation period tracking\n",
    "\n",
    "In several projects, HR teams asked for a report of employees still within their probation window — the client used 6 months as the standard. This is straightforward: anyone hired on or after January 2024 and still active.\n",
    "\n",
    "This was one of the OTBI reports I used to build manually. Here it's just a filter.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "b97628af",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "probation_list = df[df[\"in_probation\"] == True][\n",
    "    [\"person_number\", \"first_name\", \"last_name\", \"department_code\", \"hire_date\", \"grade\"]\n",
    "].sort_values(\"hire_date\", ascending=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Employees currently in probation period: {len(probation_list)}\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(probation_list.to_string(index=False))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "56a27181",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
  
    "\n",
    "In real projects I would send the client a clean file listing every flagged record with the reason, so they could fix it in their source system before the next HDL load.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "90539805",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "flagged = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for _, row in dupes.iterrows():\n",
    "    flagged.append({\"person_number\": row[\"person_number\"], \"issue\": \"Duplicate person number\"})\n",
    "\n",
    "for _, row in missing_name.iterrows():\n",
    "    flagged.append({\"person_number\": row[\"person_number\"], \"issue\": \"Missing first name\"})\n",
    "\n",
    "for _, row in bad_dates.iterrows():\n",
    "    flagged.append({\"person_number\": row[\"person_number\"], \"issue\": \"Hire date after termination date\"})\n",
    "\n",
    "for _, row in future_hire.iterrows():\n",
    "    flagged.append({\"person_number\": row[\"person_number\"], \"issue\": \"Future hire date on active employee\"})\n",
    "\n",
    "for _, row in invalid_dept.iterrows():\n",
    "    flagged.append({\"person_number\": row[\"person_number\"], \"issue\": f\"Invalid department code: {row['department_code']}\"})\n",
    "\n",
    "for _, row in outliers.iterrows():\n",
    "    flagged.append({\"person_number\": row[\"person_number\"], \"issue\": f\"Salary outlier (z={row['z_score']:.1f}) for grade {row['grade']}\"})\n",
    "\n",
    "flagged_df = pd.DataFrame(flagged).drop_duplicates()\n",
    "flagged_df.to_csv(\"flagged_records.csv\", index=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Total flagged records exported: {len(flagged_df)}\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(flagged_df.head(15).to_string(index=False))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6e3e0b2e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 12. What I do differently with real data\n",
    "\n",
    "A few things this notebook doesn't handle that come up in real migrations:\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Effective dating**\n",
    "Oracle HCM is date-effective — every change creates a new row with an effective start and end date. The duplicate check here is simplified. In reality you'd need to check for overlapping date ranges on the same person number, not just exact duplicates.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. Cross-object validation**\n",
    "The department code check here uses a hardcoded list. In a real project you'd pull the valid codes directly from the HCM setup tables (or from a reference HDL load) and compare dynamically.\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. HDL error logs**\n",
    "The real output of a bad load is an `.out` file with row-level errors. A useful next step would be parsing that file automatically and mapping errors back to source rows — something I had to do manually every time.\n",
    "\n",
    "**4. Volume**\n",
    "300 records is small. Real migrations I worked on had 10,000+ records. Pandas handles that fine, but the flagged records export becomes more important when you can't eyeball the data directly.\n"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "metadata": {},
 "nbformat": 4,
 "nbformat_minor": 5
}
